text: Second week of precon league this week, and Mathis is playing out just as badly as I had assumed in that he actively makes people attack you.
Apparently he played quite well in the 1v1 tournament at my local shop though
Is Mathas player focusing on one person or multiple? I feel like single focus is better
He tried both, but it really doesn't matter, there's just no situation where bounties work
What's the best case scenario with a bounty on a creature in a four player game?
You convince people to take out things you want gone
So presumably you're putting a bounty on a creature that isn't an instant must-kill?
Since nobody needs to be convinced to kill a Vorinclex or something
Say you've got a couple of beatass fliers and there's a Vampire Nighthawk in the way that you'd like gone, so you're gonna bounty it up and convince someone to do the dirty work for you
One strategy is target critters of the person on the lead and convince the tAble you're trying to help folks catch up.

That's the situation where he probably works best. It feels like a pretty narrow slice of commander where drawing a couple of cards is going to even the game back up without instead catapulting someone else ahead, but in theory I can see how that sometimes is a thing

I'm not sure I'd build a deck that really only works when we're playing archenemy. Building around the table losing seems a strange mindset to brew with, but in that situation that's probably where he functions best
Political decks are hard to build and pilot in general and their effectiveness is pretty meta-dependent.
I think it requires some table talk with a good speaker.
Yes, exactly
People keep saying that, but I still don't understand what someone is going to say that makes me forget how card advantage works
I'm not trying to be obstinate or anything, I just absolutely don't get it the thought process
Because good political decks appeal to greed/emotion vs your analytical side.
Edric certainly makes people stupid sometimes

That one I get though. You've got four fliers and you swing elsewhere because four cards just for you is a lot. The Mathas reward seems too meager, requires more work, and you simultaneously see other people reap the rewards of what you've done
Fully agree that politics is an emotional meta game.
It seems way, way less tempting
Now you're talking implementation vs archetype.
I think that's why you help the weakest member. So your card draw is better than theirs. You don't help the guy in first place or second if you're first.
Can you avoid helping them though? All three draw
The only one who doesn't is the guy who lost the critter

I think the big thing for political decks is what the endgoal is in mind. If you're trying to win every game, maybe a political based deck isn't the best? I think if you're trying to steward gameplay and as much social interaction as possible they're a fine choice, but if you're strictly looking at wins and losses decks like Mathias just don't seem to lend themselves to that goal, not even an archetype decision.
I agree with <@U4V5EHQ2G> that Mathas' design is a little flawed for true politics. If only the person who kills the creature EXCEPT the owner drew the card it would be better

<@U33EGB4TX> I get the playing for fun part where you don't care about wins/losses, but if that's the case you're probably way better off with a Pheldagriff style hugs deck where in theory everyone is happy. Mathas is always gonna have one person losing stuff to give the rewards.
I mean, I'll still kill you first for helping everyone, but I get why someone would play that :stuck_out_tongue:
What if Matthas put a bounty counter on a player and, until your next turn, all creatures that player owns have bounty counters on them? The counters only give the draw to the person doing the kill.
Feels much more tempting to me for sure
And much more political
I agree that the current implementation is a little too hug-like for Mardu.
I think that might be "too mean" for Wizards to get behind. But I'm biased because I enjoy political decks, so who am I to say :grin:
They could limit the reward to the person doing the kill and the Mathas player and it would be better.
Actually, that's a good point. Mardu politics seems like it might need to basically be ruthless aggression. Control the board and punish those that try not to follow along.
Limit it to one creature
So basically have Mathas a Commander version of the new Curse cycle?
